<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910128-0027</DOCNO><DOCID>910128-0027.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Pittston Co.:   Firm Posts Strong Results   For Year, Fourth Quarter</HL><DATE>01/28/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3B</SO><CO>   PCO</CO><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)COAL PRODUCERS (COA)</IN><LP>   Pittston Co. reported strong fourth-quarter results andrecord full-year earnings as it continued to rebound from astrike-impaired 1989.   The Greenwich, Conn., company, which produces coal and hasinternational air freight and private security businesses,said net income for the quarter was $25.4 million, or 68cents a share, compared with a net loss of $18.8 million, or50 cents a share, a year earlier. The quarter included a gainof $5.4 million on tax-loss carry-forwards; the 1989 quarterincluded a charge in the same amount. Sales rose 21% to$490.1 million.</LP><TEXT>   For the year, the company posted net income of $61.1million, or $1.64 a share, compared with $3.8 million, or 10cents a share, a year ago. The 1990 results included a gainof $14.9 million. Sales rose 13% to $1.85 billion.   Pittston said that the full-year results were the best ina decade. Paul Douglas, chairman and chief executive officer,said all businesses performed well in the quarter despite theweakening economy, and its Brinks armored-car and homesecurity businesses did particularly well. Burlington AirExpress, which accounts for about half of Pittston's sales,showed modest improvement in operations.</TEXT></DOC>